04447nam a22006375i 9780292748545DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927485457 a10.7560/7485382doi  a(DE-B1597)587978  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aBX1466.3bM97 2013eb 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a282 .810822231 aMyscofski, Carole A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmazons, Wives, Nuns, and Witches :bWomen and the Catholic Church in Colonial Brazil, 1500-1822 /cCarole A. Myscofski. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Amazons and Others -- tChapter one. Amazons and Cannibals: Imagining Brazilian Women in the Colonial Period -- tChapter two. The Body of Virtues: The Christian Ideal for Brazilian Women -- tChapter three. Reading, Writing, and Sewing: Education for Brazilian Women -- tChapter four. Before the Church Doors: Women as Wives and Concubines -- tChapter five. Freiras and Recolhidas: The Reclusive Life for Brazilian Women -- tChapter six. Women and Magic: Religious Dissidents in Colonial Brazil -- tConclusion. Closing the Colonial Era -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Roman Catholic church played a dominant role in colonial Brazil, so that women’s lives in the colony were shaped and constrained by the Church’s ideals for pure women, as well as by parallel concepts in the Iberian honor code for women. Records left by Jesuit missionaries, Roman Catholic church officials, and Portuguese Inquisitors make clear that women’s daily lives and their opportunities for marriage, education, and religious practice were sharply circumscribed throughout the colonial period. Yet these same documents also provide evocative glimpses of the religious beliefs and practices that were especially cherished or independently developed by women for their own use, constituting a separate world for wives, mothers, concubines, nuns, and witches. Drawing on extensive original research in primary manuscript and printed sources from Brazilian libraries and archives, as well as secondary Brazilian historical works, Carole Myscofski proposes to write Brazilian women back into history, to understand how they lived their lives within the society created by the Portuguese imperial government and Luso-Catholic ecclesiastical institutions. Myscofski offers detailed explorations of the Catholic colonial views of the ideal woman, the patterns in women’s education, the religious views on marriage and sexuality, the history of women’s convents and retreat houses, and the development of magical practices among women in that era. One of the few wide-ranging histories of women in colonial Latin America, this book makes a crucial contribution to our knowledge of the early modern Atlantic World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCatholic womenzBrazil. 0aWomen and religionzBrazil. 0aWomen in the Catholic ChurchzBrazil. 0aWomenxReligious lifezBrazil. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292748545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292748545/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK